How neural activity in the brain translates into the æmindÆ is a critical question facing psychology and cognitive science.  Housed in the recently constructed Psychology Building on the Oxford campus, the Center for Psychophysiology enables access to modern cognitive and behavioral neuroscience technologies. The acquisition of these systems has allowed researchers from a broad range to disciplines to augment their current behavioral methodologies with a variety of noninvasive means of measuring and modeling human brain function.

The continuous, scalp-recorded EEG and its derivative, event-related potentials (ERP), provide windows into the brain activities that underlie psychological processing. This technology measures brain activity by recording rapid changes in the electromagnetic fields generated by neurons as they engage in processing. High-density (e.g., 256 channel) EEG systems makes it possible to identify the sources of this electrophysiological activity. By taking advantage of recent advances in mathematical modeling techniques, this spatial information can be used to localize activity observed in the EEG signal to specific parts of the brain, and thus clarify the relationship between neural activity and psychological function.  

Projects supported by the acquisition of the EEG systems span multiple disciplines, some of which involve cross-disciplinary collaborations including relating neural activation to working memory and category learning, identifying the neural correlates of value in decision-making, measuring brain activities during play in young children, and contrasting the neural components of same-race and other-race face recognition.  Three studies have produced results that have been presented at major international and national conferences.  These include showing that childrenÆs cognitive processing during generative video games versus simple response learning games involves a greater contribution of the working memory system that is critical to broader learning and development.  Another finding documents that mathematical models of working memory that characterizes the system as æslotsÆ of available resources found support in the dynamics of neural activity.

In addition to supporting faculty and student research efforts, this acquisition also allowed the Center to offer a unique undergraduate curriculum in psychophysiology and cognitive neuroscience that embodies the "Student as Scholar" learning model that is at the heart of MiamiÆs undergraduate mission.  Selected students obtained hands-on experiences in the collection and analysis of EEG data, broadened their knowledge to include applications outside of their own specific disciplines, and designed and conducted independent research projects in their final year of study (e.g., senior or honorÆs theses).  This tiered curriculum initiative is one-of-a kind in its focus on undergraduate training as it relates to science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) disciplines, and is exemplary of MiamiÆs goal of creating the engaged learner.


